value.value: Ornithine carbamoyltransferase, mitochondrial (354 aa, ~40 kDa) is encoded by the human OTC gene. This protein plays a role in the metabolism of ornithine.
This gene is involved in the modulation of neuronal migration.

Human PAFAH1B1 wild-type allele is located in the vicinity of 17p13.3 and is approximately 92 kb in length. This allele, which encodes platelet-activating factor acetylhydrolase, isoform Ib, alpha subunit protein, plays a role in the regulation of neuronal migration. Mutations in the gene are associated with lissencephaly type 1, subcortical band heterotopia, and Miller-Dieker lissencephaly syndrome.

label.value: Platelet-Activating Factor Acetylhydrolase IB Subunit Alpha

value.value: Platelet-activating factor acetylhydrolase IB subunit alpha (410 aa, ~47 kDa) is encoded by the human PAFAH1B1 gene. This protein is involved in neuronal migration.
This gene plays a role in transcriptional regulation.

Human PAX6 wild-type allele is located in the vicinity of 11p13 and is approximately 29 kb in length. This allele, which encodes paired box protein Pax-6, plays a role in the mediation of transcription. Mutations in the gene are associated with a number of congenital disorders of the eye.
Paired box protein Pax-6 (422 aa, ~47 kDa) is encoded by the human PAX6 gene. This protein plays a role in transcription.
This gene is involved in both the development of the pancreas and transcriptional regulation.

Human PITX2 wild-type allele is located within 4q25-q27 and is approximately 25 kb in length. This allele, which encodes pituitary homeobox 2 protein, plays a role in both the modulation of transcription and the regulation of pancreatic development. Mutations in the gene are associated with Rieger syndrome type 1, iridogoniodysgenesis type 2, Peters anomaly, and ring dermoid of cornea.
Pituitary homeobox 2 (317 aa, ~35 kDa) is encoded by the human PITX2 gene. This protein is involved in transcriptional regulation during pancreatic development.
This gene plays a role in kidney development.

Human PKD1 wild-type allele is located in the vicinity of 16p13.3 and is approximately 47 kb in length. This allele, which encodes polycystin-1 protein, is involved in the development of the kidney. Mutations in the gene are associated with polycystic kidney disease autosomal dominant type 1.
Polycystin-1 (4303 aa, ~463 kDa) is encoded by the human PKD1 gene. This protein may play a role in protein-protein and protein-carbohydrate interactions during kidney development.
This gene is involved in neuronal development.

Human PLP1 wild-type allele is located in the vicinity of Xq22 and is approximately 16 kb in length. This allele, which encodes myelin proteolipid protein, plays a role in the modulation of neuronal development and function. Mutation of the gene is associated with both Pelizaeus-Merzbacher disease and spastic paraplegia type 2.
Myelin proteolipid protein (277 aa, ~30 kDa) is encoded by the human PLP1 gene. This protein is involved in the structure of the myelin sheath.
A class or organic compounds composed of carbon, hydrogen, and nitrogen containing two or more amino groups with some compounds acting as essential growth factors for microorganisms.
This protein plays a role in the maintenance of myelin.

Human PMP22 wild-type allele is located within 17p12-p11.2 and is approximately 36 kb in length. This allele, which encodes peripheral myelin protein 22, plays a role in the modulation of the structure of myelin. Mutation of the gene is associated with Charcot-Marie-Tooth disease Types IA and IE, Dejerine-Sottas syndrome, inflammatory demyelinating polyneuropathy and hereditary neuropathy with liability to pressure palsies.
Peripheral myelin protein 22 (160 aa, ~18 kDa) is encoded by the human PMP22 gene. This protein is involved in the determination of the structure and deposition of myelin.

label.value: International Unit per Milligram of Creatinine

value.value: A unit of arbitrary substance concentration with biologic activity defined as the concentration of international unit(s) per milligram of creatinine.
A dose calculation unit expressed in microgram(s) per milliliter of solution per period of time equal to sixty minutes.
A means of finding a solution to a problem, or a means of finding agreement or harmony.
One of the points that define a graph.
Least in number, quantity, magnitude or extent of those under consideration.

A nerve that arises from the second, third, and fourth lumbar nerves and enters the thigh through the obturator canal. It is responsible for the sensory innervation of the skin of the medial aspect of the thigh and also responsible for the motor innervation of the adductor muscles of the lower extremity.
A lung carcinoma characterized by the presence of large or small neuroendocrine carcinoma cells in combination with malignant glandular or squamous epithelial cells.
Anterior to or preceding the sacrum.
The best or most suitable; the greatest degree attainable.
The resistance of a liquid to sheer forces and flow.
The rate at which a substance is removed from the blood via the kidneys.

A set of objects called points, nodes, or vertices connected by a binary relation between vertices called lines or edges. It is a mathematical structure used to model pairwise relations between objects from a certain collection.
A relation in which no element is in relation to itself.
A relation in which each element is in relation to itself.
A binary relation such that if a is related to b then b is related to a.
A binary relation such that if a is related to b and b is related to a, then a equals b.
A binary relation such that whenever an element a is related to an element b, and b is in turn related to an element c, then a is also related to c.
A binary relation such that an element a is related to an element b, and b is in turn related to an element c, but a is not related to c.
A connection between nodes in a graph.
An injection (or injective, or one-to-one) such that for every y in Y there is at most one x in X such that f(x) equals y.
An surjection (or surjective, or onto) such that for every y in Y there is at least one x in X such that f(x) equals y.

A quinacrine mustard compound with potential antineoplastic activity. Amustaline binds to, intercalates and crosslinks DNA and RNA. This agent is mainly used for ex vivo purposes, specifically for the inactivation of pathogens such as viruses, protozoa and bacteria in red blood cells (RBCs).

The active metabolite of cilazapril, a pyridazine angiotensin-converting enzyme (ACE) inhibitor with antihypertensive activity. As a prodrug, cilazapril is rapidly metabolized in the liver to cilazaprilat; cilazaprilat competitively binds to and inhibits ACE, thereby blocking the conversion of angiotensin I to angiotensin II. This prevents the potent vasoconstrictive actions of angiotensin II, resulting in vasodilation. Cilazaprilat also decreases angiotensin II-induced aldosterone secretion by the adrenal cortex, which leads to an increase in sodium excretion and subsequently increases water outflow.
